<div id="review_2977068785" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2977068785" />
    <a title="ALLEN" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58158333-allen"><img alt="ALLEN" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578421145p2/58158333.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2977068785?book_show_action=true">Sep 14, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="ALLEN" class="user" itemprop="url" name="ALLEN" href="/user/show/58158333-allen">ALLEN</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2977068785" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10706090796960220854">This is not my favorite John Grisham novel, nor has it aged particularly well since the mid-1990s, when it was first published. The story of a major products-liability contest that pits Big Tobacco vs. Plaintiffs&apos; Rights, in John Grisham&apos;s knowledgeable hands, becomes a story not so much of good versus evil as the despicable versus the contemptible. While the jurors themselves are far from innocent, they are but pawns in this big-money game in which things aren&apos;t ever what they should be, and ra</span>
  <span id="freeText10706090796960220854" style="display:none">This is not my favorite John Grisham novel, nor has it aged particularly well since the mid-1990s, when it was first published. The story of a major products-liability contest that pits Big Tobacco vs. Plaintiffs' Rights, in John Grisham's knowledgeable hands, becomes a story not so much of good versus evil as the despicable versus the contemptible. While the jurors themselves are far from innocent, they are but pawns in this big-money game in which things aren't ever what they should be, and rarely seem to be. It is great that Grisham lets us in on he central workings of this cynical machine, but the cynicism may be too much for some. Don't forget, there's a good movie out there too, though by the time it was made (2003), the offending product had been changed to handguns. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10706090796960220854" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


