<div id="review_878802319" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/878802319" />
    <a title="D.R." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15794288-d-r"><img alt="D.R." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591201147p2/15794288.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/878802319?book_show_action=true">Mar 11, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="D.R." class="user" itemprop="url" name="D.R." href="/user/show/15794288-d-r">D.R.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer878802319" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13235492850012494126">Anyone who’s been on a jury, and even those who haven’t, will appreciate Grisham’s The Runaway Jury.<br/> <br/>Big tobacco companies are on the defense against claims by a widow that tobacco ruined her husband’s life and eventually killed him prematurely at the age of 53. Hundreds of millions of dollars and the future of the tobacco industry are at stake if the case is lost, thereby opening the door for huge class action lawsuits. <br/><br/>The tobacco companies hire the villain of the novel, Rankin Fitch, to make </span>
  <span id="freeText13235492850012494126" style="display:none">Anyone who’s been on a jury, and even those who haven’t, will appreciate Grisham’s The Runaway Jury.<br /> <br />Big tobacco companies are on the defense against claims by a widow that tobacco ruined her husband’s life and eventually killed him prematurely at the age of 53. Hundreds of millions of dollars and the future of the tobacco industry are at stake if the case is lost, thereby opening the door for huge class action lawsuits. <br /><br />The tobacco companies hire the villain of the novel, Rankin Fitch, to make sure they don’t lose the case. He breaks every law in the books as he attempts to coerce members of the jury into siding with the tobacco companies. What Fitch hadn’t anticipated was Nicholas Easter, jury member #2, who intentionally worked his way onto the jury for the sole purpose of getting access to some of that tobacco money. <br /><br />Under the direction of Marlee, Easter’s partner and love interest, Easter takes control of the jury and blackmails Fitch to pay a large ransom to deliver a not guilty verdict. Marlee had personal motivation for getting even with the tobacco companies, and she’d prepared for years for this opportunity. What happens next was not anticipated, at least not by me. <br /> <br />I’m not sure everything that Easter, Marlee, and Fitch pulled off in the novel couldn't easily be done, if at all. A mistrial would likely be declared if even a portion of what transpired in this novel were to actually occur in a real trial, but it doesn’t matter. The story was fast moving, the characters compelling, and gave you plenty to cheer and to hate. And isn’t that what a reader wants? <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13235492850012494126" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

